\subsection{A geometric extension treated separately}

A second class of Koide-type claim involves geometric constructions on the lepton triple rather than algebraic relations among quark masses. One such construction---the squared outer Soddy curvature of the Koide-saturating lepton triple, evaluated at the scale $\Sigma m_\ell$, compared against $m_s$---has been examined in a separate preprint~\citep{Brilliant2026strange}. The present note's framework does not directly transfer: that construction is a closed-form prediction of one output ($m_s$) from a specific geometric invariant of the lepton triple, not a search over a space of (triple, sign, scale) combinations, so the LEE machinery developed here does not apply in the same way. The Model~A random-spectrum null is also not the appropriate reference class for a single geometric prediction. The analogous concerns for that construction---multiplicity over choice of geometric invariant, choice of evaluation scale, and the data-dependent hypothesis-formation issue if the construction was identified on the current $m_s$ value---require their own treatment, and the temporal-trajectory test of Section~\ref{sec:temporal} is the most directly transferable element. We defer that analysis to follow-up work.

\subsection{Limitations}

The search space is finite, discrete, and physically interpretable; it does not exhaust all conceivable Koide-type formulations. A continuous scale scan would inflate the trial count and the implied LEE penalty without bound, so the present discrete audit should be read as a lower-complexity benchmark, not an exhaustive accounting. We do not vary the algebraic target ($Q = 2/3$ throughout), the mass scheme ($\overline{\text{MS}}$ only), or the fermion content (no neutrinos, no boson masses).

The Model~A prior is conditional on perturbative validity, implemented by rejection sampling (Section~\ref{sec:loss-bias}); this is an explicit feature of the chosen reference class. Within CRunDec the rejected set is loop-order-independent (same draws fail at all CRunDec loop orders); across alternative running engines the rejected set differs (the analytic 1-loop scheme has $13.4\%$ rejection vs.\ $32.7\%$ for full CRunDec), so the conditional prior is engine-dependent across alternatives. We report 4-loop CRunDec values throughout. Reported tail fractions are conditional on the perturbatively-valid log-uniform reference class as defined by 4-loop CRunDec, which is one of several defensible choices.

The 1/2/3/4/5-loop convergence study (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}) shows the absolute Model~A tail probabilities for \emph{running} claims to vary by $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across the four orders at which the observed Koide combination has perturbatively converged ($\{1, 3, 4, 5\}$); the 2-loop value is reported but flagged as reflecting non-convergence of the observed Koide combination itself ($|Q - 2/3|$ an order of magnitude larger than at higher orders). \emph{Self-scale} claims (Cao, Rivero, chain-no-run, 20-triple self) are perfectly stable across all five loop orders. All reported Model~A numbers in the main text use 4-loop running.

Sensitivity of the two null models is examined in Section~\ref{sec:robustness}, where the running implementation, the random-spectrum prior family, the assumption of uncorrelated FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and the rejection-sampling reframe are each tested.

The Model~B baseline treats FLAG/PDG quark mass uncertainties as Gaussian and uncorrelated. Realistic lattice and PDG averages have shared systematic structure (common scale-setting, common decay-constant inputs, common $\alpha_s$) that our $\rho$-grid sensitivity analysis (Section~\ref{sec:correlation-sensitivity}) probes only with simple common-correlation assumptions, not with empirical covariance matrices. Quantitative Model~B values---including the hit-count expectation discussed in Section~\ref{sec:results}---should therefore be read as approximate. Since Model~B is itself a descriptive diagnostic rather than an inferential test (Section~\ref{sec:interpretation}), this limitation primarily affects descriptive precision rather than inferential conclusions, but readers should not over-interpret the precise Model~B numbers.

The Model~A reference class draws six masses i.i.d.\ log-uniformly and sorts them; the resulting hierarchy and gap distributions are not derived from any physical principle and are not validated to preserve the relevant nuisance structure of $Q$ (the way $Q$ depends on the joint distribution of mass ratios, rather than on individual masses). The hierarchy-preserving null variants in Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null} partially address this by injecting empirical SM gap structure, but they too are analyst constructions. Different choices of how to encode hierarchy structure in the prior would yield different Model~A tail fractions; this is an additional component of the reference-class scope question (Section~\ref{sec:model-a}) and another reason to read Model~A values as within-construction relative rankings.


\section{Conclusion}
\label{sec:conclusion}

Under the two tools audited here, at full search freedom the observed closures reproduce the median null residual, yielding tail probability $\approx 0.50$ under the 4-loop Model~A random-spectrum null and $\approx 0.50$ under the Model~B measurement-noise bootstrap. A matched-complexity knob-isolation test (Section~\ref{sec:isolation}, Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}) indicates that admitting non-self-scale running is a distinct contributor to the Model~A noise floor beyond what trial-count multiplicity alone produces. Sensitivity checks (Section~\ref{sec:robustness}) indicate that the full-search qualitative result is stable under the running implementation, under the choice of prior family within the tested range, under plausible correlation structure in the FLAG/PDG uncertainties, and under the rejection-sampling reframe of the perturbative-validity conditioning. The absolute Model~A tail probabilities for running claims carry a loop-order spread of $\approx 0.05$--$0.13$ across orders 1, 3, 4, 5 and reach $\approx 0.5$ when 2-loop is included (Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}; the 2-loop full-search value of $\approx 0.04$ is explained by perturbative non-convergence of the observed Koide combination at 2-loop). Across all five loop orders the qualitative ranking is preserved.

Pre-specified single-triple claims occupy an intermediate position. The $(c,b,t)$ closure at $\mu = m_\tau$ has a baseline Model~A tail probability of $\approx 0.003$, $\approx 0.004$--$0.007$ under hierarchy-preserving variants, and a Model~B tail probability of $\approx 0.15$ that restates its observed residual ratio $|r|/\sigma_Q \approx 0.09$. The claim was published by the present author in~\citep{Brilliant2026cbt} prior to the present audit, and the audit began as a sanity check on that claim before being extended to the full quark-side search space; the present analysis therefore provides a multiplicity-corrected restatement of a prior author claim under the chosen log-uniform prior class and 4-loop running, not an independent confirmation. The temporal trajectory of its residual across future FLAG/PDG releases (Section~\ref{sec:temporal}, Table~\ref{tab:drift}) is what a subsequent forward-looking evaluation would draw on.

The analysis, all code, all seeds, and the audited trial list are in the repository~\citep{RepoMC}.


\section*{Computational note}

All computations are reproducible from~\citep{RepoMC}. Search space: \texttt{search\_space.json} ($12{,}960$ trials, audited in \texttt{trial\_list\_complete.csv}). Running: four-loop $\overline{\text{MS}}$ via \texttt{CRunDec}~\citep{CRunDec}, with thresholds computed from the input mass spectrum (SM values for Models~A and~B baseline; perturbed values for bootstrap variants; random values for random-spectrum draws). Inputs: FLAG~2024, PDG~2024.

Random-spectrum MC (Model~A): $100{,}000$ retained experiments in the main run (rejection-sampling acceptance rate $\approx 67\%$ from the unconditioned log-uniform prior; an earlier $10{,}000$-experiment run gave values agreeing within $1$--$2$ SE), full CRunDec on every retained draw. Bootstrap MC (Model~B): $2{,}000$ experiments per correlation variant, full CRunDec on every draw, with perturbations applied uniformly to all claims including self-scale-only claims (an earlier draft implementation evaluated self-scale claims at unperturbed central values; this has been corrected). Surrogate validation: $500$ paired draws comparing surrogate to full CRunDec (the surrogate failed validation and was not used in the final analysis). Hierarchy-preserving null: $10{,}000$ experiments per variant. Matched-complexity knob-isolation test: $K = 1000$ random subsamples of size $N' \in \{40, 80, 160, 320, 640, 1280, 2560, 3240\}$ drawn from each of the signs-only ($80$), running-only ($3{,}240$), and full-search ($12{,}960$) trial pools. Loop-order convergence study: $N = 10{,}000$ paired draws at 1-, 2-, 3-, 4-, and 5-loop CRunDec (the 2-loop value is reported alongside the others; its dramatic deviation from 1/3/4/5-loop reflects perturbative non-convergence of the observed Koide combination at 2-loop, documented in Section~\ref{sec:loop-order}). Analytic 1-loop crosscheck: pure-Python closed-form $\alpha_s(\mu)$ with simplified threshold matching, $N = 10{,}000$ paired draws (rejection rate $13.4\%$ vs.\ $32.7\%$ for full CRunDec, reflecting differing perturbative-validity regions). Rejection-sampling reframe consistency check: explicit rejection sampling implementation drawing $14{,}783$ unconditioned attempts to obtain $10{,}000$ retained valid spectra; resulting tail probabilities agree with the original implementation within MC noise. Distributional comparison of rejected vs.\ retained subsamples: $3{,}269$ rejected vs.\ $6{,}731$ retained under surrogate running. All seeds documented in the repository.


