\subsection{Interpretation}
\label{sec:interpretation}

Null Model~A asks whether the closure is unusual relative to a generic random spectrum. Pre-specified single-triple claims (those proposed in prior literature before the present audit; see Section~\ref{sec:discussion}) have smaller Model~A tail probabilities within the chosen prior class than the full search.

Null Model~B asks whether the closure is distinguishable from measurement noise on the actual masses. Most claims with $|r| \gg \sigma_Q$ return Model~B tail probabilities near $0.5$. The exception is the $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ family of claims, for which $|r| \approx 0.09 \sigma_Q$ and the Model~B tail probability is accordingly small ($\approx 0.15$); this number restates the $r/\sigma_Q$ ratio and does not add evidential content.

The two models are answering different questions and should not be read as giving convergent evidence on a common inferential target. Model~A's tail probabilities are conditional on the random-spectrum prior and its hierarchy-preserving variants (Section~\ref{sec:hierarchy-null}); Model~B's tail probabilities are conditional on the bootstrap around current FLAG/PDG central values and are approximately determined by $r/\sigma_Q$. A claim's posture under each is reported separately and should be interpreted separately; the two cannot be combined into a single summary tail probability.

A claim with a low Model~A tail probability but a typical Model~B tail probability is unusual relative to the chosen random-spectrum prior class but has $|r| \gg \sigma_Q$. A claim with typical tail probabilities under both is fully consistent with noise under the chosen Model~A prior class and with measurement-noise perturbations around the observed spectrum. A claim with a low Model~A tail probability and a small Model~B tail probability is unusual relative to the chosen random-spectrum prior class and has $|r| \ll \sigma_Q$. Neither model, nor their combination, addresses whether a relation identified by this framework reflects underlying structure in nature; that is a separate question about physical meaningfulness that the present audit does not try to answer.

\paragraph{Three distinct inferential targets.} It is useful to separate three questions that are easy to conflate:
\begin{enumerate}
\item \textbf{Is the full search unusual?} ``Across the audited 12{,}960 (triple, sign, scale) configurations, is finding \emph{some} closure as good as the observed best closure unusual under the random-spectrum reference?'' Answered by Model~A applied to the full search; result is $T \approx 0.50$.
\item \textbf{Is a particular literature-fixed claim unusual under the audit?} ``Is the residual of a single triple/sign/scale configuration proposed in prior work unusual within the same reference class?'' Answered by Model~A applied per-claim; results are in Table~\ref{tab:pvalues}.
\item \textbf{Is a particular configuration locally consistent with measurement noise?} ``How small is the observed residual relative to the propagated mass-measurement uncertainty for that configuration?'' Answered by Model~B; results are approximately the $|r|/\sigma_Q$ ratio.
\end{enumerate}
These are different questions answered by different statistics. The Model~A full-search answer (target~1) does not depend on prior literature; the Model~A per-claim answers (target~2) are conditional on which claims one chooses to single out; the Model~B answers (target~3) are descriptive measurement-precision statements. We report all three and do not combine them into a single composite ranking.

\paragraph{Scope of the multiplicity correction.} The look-elsewhere correction implemented by Model~A bounds multiplicity within the audited search space (the enumerated 12{,}960 configurations and the chosen reference class). It does \emph{not} bound the broader hypothesis-generation degrees of freedom---the four decades of Koide literature, the choice of Koide-style algebraic targets, the iterative selection of evaluation scales by individual researchers, or the present author's own prior selection that motivated the audit. No look-elsewhere correction in any field bounds all unenumerable researcher choices; standard practice is that post-hoc multiplicity corrections bound the explicit search and the broader question is deferred to forward-looking tests on independent data~\citep{CousinsLectures}. The temporal-trajectory analysis of Section~\ref{sec:temporal} treats present-day claims as pre-registered against future FLAG/PDG releases and is the relevant forward-looking test; the per-claim Model~A tail fractions in Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} should be read as within-audit rank statements only.


\section{Sensitivity of the null models}
\label{sec:robustness}

The two null models above each rest on assumptions a referee may reasonably question: that the running implementation is faithful, that the random-spectrum prior is a fair reference, that uncorrelated Gaussian perturbations capture the measurement-uncertainty structure, and that pseudo-experiments lost to numerical failure do not bias the result. We test each.

\subsection{Validation of surrogate running}
\label{sec:surrogate-validation}

An earlier implementation of Model~A used a surrogate running scheme, applying the same multiplicative ratios as the four-loop calculation but skipping the full CRunDec call per draw, for computational efficiency. To verify the surrogate, we recomputed a fixed-seed subsample of 500 Model~A pseudo-experiments using full four-loop CRunDec and compared per-draw best residuals across the $12{,}960$ trials.

The surrogate did not meet the validation criteria. The median fractional discrepancy in the per-draw best residual was $92\%$; the same trial was identified as best under both methods in only $0.2\%$ of draws; tail-probability confidence intervals at thresholds $\{10^{-3}, 10^{-4}, 10^{-5}\}$ did not overlap. The surrogate applied SM-derived multiplicative ratios to random spectra whose thresholds and flavor structure are different, and the approximation broke down per-draw.

We set aside the surrogate and rebuilt Model~A using full four-loop CRunDec on every draw (Section~\ref{sec:mc}, Null Model~A). Comparison of the rebuilt Model~A $T$s to the surrogate values for the nine claims of Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} showed the qualitative ranking preserved: the same five claims meet $T < 0.05$, and the author-pre-specified $(c,b,t)$ at $\mu = m_\tau$ claim moved from $T = 0.005$ to $T = 0.002$. The agreement at the level of tail probabilities, despite the per-draw discrepancy, is fortunate but not relied upon: all numbers reported in Sections~\ref{sec:isolation} and~\ref{sec:discussion} use the full-CRunDec values.

\subsection{Hierarchy-preserving variant of Model A}
\label{sec:hierarchy-null}

Independent log-uniform draws ignore the fact that the SM quark spectrum is hierarchical: the log-mass gaps $\log m_{i+1} - \log m_i$ have a structured distribution that random independent draws do not reproduce. To test whether this matters for the Table~\ref{tab:pvalues} ranking, we re-ran Model~A under two hierarchy-preserving variants. Variant~A draws gaps as multiplicative jitter, $\Delta'_i = \Delta_i \cdot U(0.5, 2.0)$, around the empirical SM gaps; Variant~B draws gaps from an exponential distribution matched to the empirical mean. In both, the spectrum is constructed by cumulative sum from a randomly anchored minimum. Each variant uses $N = 10{,}000$ pseudo-experiments through the full $12{,}960$-trial search with full CRunDec.

