The three configurations in Table~\ref{tab:phase1} differ in both type and number of admitted trials (80, 3{,}240, 12{,}960). The raw tail probabilities therefore cannot be compared directly across rows to attribute the full-search behaviour to running per se rather than to trial-count multiplicity. To partially separate the trial-count effect from the running effect, we performed a matched-complexity bootstrap-subsample test: for each trial pool (signs-only, running-only, full search) we drew $K = 1000$ random subsamples of size $N'$ and computed the tail probability of the subsample best-residual against the Model~A null, for $N' \in \{40, 80, 160, 320, 640, 1280, 2560, 3240\}$ (the last value is the running-only pool size; signs-only is capped at $N' = 80$). The matched-$N'$ curves (Figure~\ref{fig:knob_matched_N}) do not overlap: at $N' = 80$, the median subsample tail probability is $0.38$ for signs-only, $0.61$ for running-only, and $0.52$ for the full search. Running-only is associated with a larger median tail probability than signs-only at the same trial count, suggesting that the running pool's null-distribution shape produces a different best-trial behaviour than the signs-only pool's, beyond what trial-count alone produces. We do not claim this is a clean causal decomposition: the three pools differ in trial geometry, internal dependence structure, and the shape of their per-trial residual distributions in addition to their cardinality, and matching on $N'$ alone does not control for these other differences. The matched-$N'$ comparison is therefore better read as a descriptive observation that the three pools have distinguishable null-distribution behaviours at equal trial count, not as identification of a single causal mechanism.

